    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-22T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-22T10:00:00-05:00" n="693"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d693">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 <hi rend="superscript">Lic. Martin
                        Company, Glenn L./93</hi>/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-22T11:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 22, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Telegram of August 26 and instruction of August 27,<note n="29" xml:id="d693fn29"
                        >Neither printed.</note> in regard to arms export license No. 2965. Glenn L.
                    Martin informs me that its mechanics in Hong Kong are to assemble the
                        planes.<note n="30" xml:id="d693fn30">Three airplanes, nine machine guns,
                        and various other items were shipped on Chinese vessel, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Tai Yin</hi>, to the Chinese Minister of Finance, Kung.</note> One of
                    the mechanics, Harry Roland, care Pan American Airways, is stated to have in his
                    possession a letter presumably from a consular officer, informing him that he
                    will render himself liable to fine and imprisonment if he assists the Chinese
                    Government in any way. This letter appears to have raised doubts in the minds of
                    the mechanics as to whether they can legally proceed with the assembling of the
                    planes.</p>
                <p>The Department perceives no legal or other objection to the assembling by
                    American mechanics of these planes which were legally <pb facs="0547" n="539"
                        xml:id="pg_539"/> exported. Unless circumstances unknown to the Department
                    lead you to some other conclusion, you should so inform Roland.</p>
                <p>Report by telegram giving text of the letter in question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
